    "summary": "NO — \"character\" alone too polysemous, keep full term",
    "content": "NO. \"Character\" alone is too polysemous — it means a letter, a fictional person, a moral trait, a personality profile. Once you strip \"constitutive,\" the reader has no anchor. Every occurrence of \"character\" will force them to disambiguate, which is the opposite of lightweight.\n\nIf we want something shorter for running text, \"constitutive character\" is already only two words. That's not heavy. Compare: \"transcendental apperception\" runs through hundreds of pages of Kant without anyone proposing we shorten it to \"apperception\" after the first mention. Philosophical terms earn their length.\n\nKeep \"constitutive character\" throughout. It's compact enough for running text and precise enough to do its job."
  }
}
